================================================================
        SPRING BOOT REST API — FULL NOTES
        Every Word · Every Line · Combined Meaning
================================================================


----------------------------------------------------------------
1. GET ALL USERS — @GetMapping
----------------------------------------------------------------

CODE:
    @GetMapping
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userRepository.findAll();
    }

WORD BY WORD:
    @GetMapping        → Annotation — tells Spring: listen for GET request on /users
    public             → Anyone (including HTTP requests) can call this method
    List<User>         → Return type — a collection of MULTIPLE User objects
    getAllUsers()      → Method name. Empty () = needs zero inputs
    return             → Send this back as the HTTP response
    userRepository     → The DB object injected by Spring via @Autowired
    .findAll()         → JPA built-in — runs SELECT * FROM user automatically

COMBINED MEANING:
    When GET /users is called → getAllUsers() triggers →
    findAll() runs SELECT * FROM user →
    full list converted to JSON and sent back as response.


----------------------------------------------------------------
2. GET USER BY ID — @GetMapping("/{id}")
----------------------------------------------------------------

CODE:
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public User getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
    }

WORD BY WORD:
    @GetMapping("/{id}")  → Listen for GET /users/1. { } slot changes per request
    User                  → Returns ONE single User object (not a list)
    @PathVariable         → Grabs the number from URL. /users/5 → id = 5
    Long                  → Data type for ID — large number
    id                    → Variable holding the number from URL
    .findById(id)         → Runs SELECT * FROM user WHERE id = ?
    .orElse(null)         → Safety net — if ID not found return null, don't crash

    DIFFERENCE FROM GET ALL:
    GET ALL          vs    GET BY ID
    @GetMapping            @GetMapping("/{id}")
    List<User>             User
    findAll()              findById(id)
    No input               @PathVariable id from URL
    Returns everyone       Returns one person

COMBINED MEANING:
    GET /users/1 → @PathVariable grabs id=1 from URL →
    findById(1) runs SELECT WHERE id=1 →
    if found return User, if not .orElse(null) returns null safely.


----------------------------------------------------------------
3. POST — CREATE USER — @PostMapping
----------------------------------------------------------------

CODE:
    @PostMapping
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        return userRepository.save(user);
    }

WORD BY WORD:
    @PostMapping       → HTTP POST — sending data TO server to create something
                         No /{id} because creating new, no existing ID yet
    @RequestBody       → Reads JSON from Postman body, converts it to User object
    User user          → The converted object. {"name":"Raj"} becomes User variable
    .save(user)        → No ID on object → JPA runs INSERT SQL
                         Returns saved User WITH the auto-generated ID

    DIFFERENCE FROM GET:
    @GetMapping   → receiving data FROM server
    @PostMapping  → sending data TO server to create

    @PathVariable → grabbed from URL     → /users/1
    @RequestBody  → grabbed from body    → { "name": "Raj" }

COMBINED MEANING:
    POST /users + JSON body → @RequestBody converts JSON to User object →
    save(user) sees no ID → runs INSERT SQL →
    new row created → returns user back now WITH generated ID.


----------------------------------------------------------------
4. PUT — UPDATE USER — @PutMapping("/{id}")
----------------------------------------------------------------

CODE:
    @PutMapping("/{id}")
    public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) {
        User existing = userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
        if (existing != null) {
            existing.setName(user.getName());
            existing.setEmail(user.getEmail());
            return userRepository.save(existing);
        }
        return null;
    }

WORD BY WORD:
    @PutMapping("/{id}")      → HTTP PUT — update existing. Needs /{id} to know which user
    Two parameters            → FIRST TIME using 2 inputs together:
                                 @PathVariable Long id  = which user (from URL)
                                 @RequestBody User user = new data (from body JSON)
    User existing             → Fetch OLD record from DB first before changing anything
    if (existing != null)     → Safety check. != means "not equal to"
                                 If found → proceed. If not found → skip to return null
    existing.setName(...)     → user.getName() gets new value from body
                                 existing.setName() puts it into the old DB object
    save(existing)            → existing HAS an ID → JPA runs UPDATE SQL (not INSERT)
                                 Same save() method, different behavior based on ID
    return null               → User not found at all, nothing was updated

    KEY DIFFERENCE — save() behavior:
    POST → save(user)         no ID → INSERT (create new)
    PUT  → save(existing)     has ID → UPDATE (edit existing)

COMBINED MEANING:
    PUT /users/1 + JSON body →
    id from URL = which user, @RequestBody = new data →
    findById fetches old record →
    if found: set new name/email → save(existing) runs UPDATE SQL →
    returns updated user.
    If not found → returns null.


----------------------------------------------------------------
5. DELETE — REMOVE USER — @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
----------------------------------------------------------------

CODE:
    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    public String deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        userRepository.deleteById(id);
        return "User " + id + " deleted successfully!";
    }

WORD BY WORD:
    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")   → HTTP DELETE — remove a record. Needs /{id} to know which
    String                    → Return type is String (plain text)
                                 Nothing to return after deleting — just send a message
    deleteById(id)            → JPA runs DELETE FROM user WHERE id = ?
                                 Returns nothing (void) — just deletes silently
    "User " + id + "..."      → + joins strings. If id=1 → "User 1 deleted successfully!"

    DIFFERENCE FROM OTHERS:
    All others   → returned User or List<User>
    DELETE       → returns String (just a confirmation message)
    save()       → returns the saved object
    deleteById() → returns nothing (void)

COMBINED MEANING:
    DELETE /users/1 →
    @PathVariable grabs id=1 from URL →
    deleteById(1) runs DELETE SQL, returns nothing →
    method returns plain String confirmation using + to join words.


================================================================
        MASTER SUMMARY — ALL 5 IN ONE VIEW
================================================================

    HTTP      URL              JPA Method       What happens
    -------   --------------   --------------   -------------------------
    GET       /users           findAll()        Return all rows as JSON
    GET       /users/1         findById(id)     Return one user or null
    POST      /users           save(user)       INSERT new row, return with ID
    PUT       /users/1         save(existing)   UPDATE existing row, return updated
    DELETE    /users/1         deleteById(id)   Remove row, return String message


================================================================
        KEY CONCEPTS QUICK REFERENCE
================================================================

    @GetMapping        → Listen for GET request
    @PostMapping       → Listen for POST request
    @PutMapping        → Listen for PUT request
    @DeleteMapping     → Listen for DELETE request

    @PathVariable      → Grab value FROM the URL        → /users/1
    @RequestBody       → Grab value FROM the body JSON  → {"name":"Raj"}

    findAll()          → SELECT * FROM user
    findById(id)       → SELECT * FROM user WHERE id = ?
    save() no ID       → INSERT INTO user ...
    save() with ID     → UPDATE user SET ...
    deleteById(id)     → DELETE FROM user WHERE id = ?

    Optional           → Wrapper that says "may or may not exist"
    .orElse(null)      → If found return it, if not return null safely

    List<User>         → Multiple users (collection)
    User               → Single user object
    String             → Plain text message

