----------------------------------------------------------------
1. INSTEAD OF @GetMapping  (GET ALL USERS)
----------------------------------------------------------------

WAY 1 — What you wrote (basic):
    @GetMapping
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userRepository.findAll();
    }

WAY 2 — @RequestMapping (old traditional way):
    @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.GET)
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userRepository.findAll();
    }

WAY 3 — with path written explicitly:
    @GetMapping(path = "/users")
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userRepository.findAll();
    }

WAY 4 — ResponseEntity (professional way — full control of response):
    @GetMapping
    public ResponseEntity<List<User>> getAllUsers() {
        List<User> users = userRepository.findAll();
        return ResponseEntity.ok(users);  // sends 200 OK with body
    }

WAY 5 — with produces (tells client what format you are returning):
    @GetMapping(produces = "application/json")
    public List<User> getAllUsers() {
        return userRepository.findAll();
    }

NOTES:
    @GetMapping        → shortcut, clean, introduced Spring 4.3
    @RequestMapping    → old original way, more typing, same result
    ResponseEntity     → gives you control over status code (200, 404 etc)
    produces           → tells client "I will send back JSON"


----------------------------------------------------------------
2. INSTEAD OF @GetMapping("/{id}")  (GET ONE USER)
----------------------------------------------------------------

WAY 1 — What you wrote (basic):
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public User getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
    }

WAY 2 — @RequestMapping old way:
    @RequestMapping(value = "/{id}", method = RequestMethod.GET)
    public User getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
    }

WAY 3 — @PathVariable with explicit name (URL name different from variable):
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public User getUserById(@PathVariable("id") Long userId) {
        return userRepository.findById(userId).orElse(null);
    }
    //                              ^^^          ^^^
    //                         URL name      variable name — can be different

WAY 4 — ResponseEntity (returns proper 404 if not found):
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<User> getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return userRepository.findById(id)
            .map(ResponseEntity::ok)                    // found → 200 OK
            .orElse(ResponseEntity.notFound().build()); // not found → 404
    }

WAY 5 — Return Optional directly:
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public Optional<User> getUserById(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return userRepository.findById(id);
    }

NOTES:
    orElse(null)                  → returns null if not found (basic)
    ResponseEntity.notFound()     → returns proper 404 HTTP status (professional)
    Optional<User>                → lets caller decide what to do if empty
    @PathVariable("id") Long xyz  → URL slot name and variable name can differ


----------------------------------------------------------------
3. INSTEAD OF @PostMapping  (CREATE USER)
----------------------------------------------------------------

WAY 1 — What you wrote (basic):
    @PostMapping
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        return userRepository.save(user);
    }

WAY 2 — @RequestMapping old way:
    @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.POST)
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        return userRepository.save(user);
    }

WAY 3 — ResponseEntity with 201 Created status (most correct REST way):
    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        User saved = userRepository.save(user);
        return ResponseEntity.status(201).body(saved);
        // 201 = Created — correct HTTP status for POST
    }

WAY 4 — with @Valid (validates incoming data before saving):
    @PostMapping
    public User createUser(@Valid @RequestBody User user) {
        return userRepository.save(user);
    }
    // @Valid checks rules like @NotNull @Email @Size on User fields
    // If validation fails → automatically sends 400 Bad Request

WAY 5 — with consumes (says what format body must be sent in):
    @PostMapping(consumes = "application/json")
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        return userRepository.save(user);
    }

NOTES:
    200 OK       → default, used for GET
    201 Created  → correct status for POST (something was created)
    @Valid       → adds input validation — real projects always use this
    consumes     → "I only accept JSON body"
    produces     → "I will send back JSON"


----------------------------------------------------------------
4. INSTEAD OF @PutMapping  (UPDATE USER)
----------------------------------------------------------------

WAY 1 — What you wrote (basic):
    @PutMapping("/{id}")
    public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) {
        User existing = userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
        if (existing != null) {
            existing.setName(user.getName());
            existing.setEmail(user.getEmail());
            return userRepository.save(existing);
        }
        return null;
    }

WAY 2 — @RequestMapping old way:
    @RequestMapping(value = "/{id}", method = RequestMethod.PUT)
    public User updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) {
        // same logic inside
    }

WAY 3 — ResponseEntity (proper 404 if not found):
    @PutMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<User> updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) {
        User existing = userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
        if (existing != null) {
            existing.setName(user.getName());
            existing.setEmail(user.getEmail());
            return ResponseEntity.ok(userRepository.save(existing)); // 200 OK
        }
        return ResponseEntity.notFound().build(); // 404
    }

WAY 4 — @PatchMapping (update ONLY some fields, not all):
    @PatchMapping("/{id}")
    public User partialUpdate(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) {
        User existing = userRepository.findById(id).orElse(null);
        if (existing != null) {
            if (user.getName() != null) existing.setName(user.getName());
            if (user.getEmail() != null) existing.setEmail(user.getEmail());
            // only updates fields that are actually sent
            // skips fields that are null / not sent
            return userRepository.save(existing);
        }
        return null;
    }

NOTES — PUT vs PATCH:
    PUT    → replace the ENTIRE object — must send all fields
    PATCH  → update ONLY specific fields — send only what changed
    Example:
        PUT   body must have → { "name": "Raj", "email": "raj@gmail.com" }
        PATCH body can have  → { "name": "Raj" }  (email stays unchanged)


----------------------------------------------------------------
5. INSTEAD OF @DeleteMapping  (DELETE USER)
----------------------------------------------------------------

WAY 1 — What you wrote (basic):
    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    public String deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        userRepository.deleteById(id);
        return "User " + id + " deleted successfully!";
    }

WAY 2 — @RequestMapping old way:
    @RequestMapping(value = "/{id}", method = RequestMethod.DELETE)
    public String deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        userRepository.deleteById(id);
        return "User " + id + " deleted successfully!";
    }

WAY 3 — ResponseEntity with 204 No Content (most correct REST way):
    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<Void> deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        userRepository.deleteById(id);
        return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
        // 204 = deleted successfully, nothing to return
    }

WAY 4 — Check if exists before deleting (safer):
    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<String> deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        if (userRepository.existsById(id)) {
            userRepository.deleteById(id);
            return ResponseEntity.ok("User " + id + " deleted!");
        }
        return ResponseEntity.notFound().build(); // 404 if not found
    }

NOTES:
    deleteById()     → just deletes, no check — crashes if ID not found
    existsById()     → checks first safely before deleting
    204 No Content   → correct HTTP status for DELETE (nothing to return)
    200 OK + String  → simpler but not fully correct REST standard
    Void             → means literally nothing returned in body


