================================================================
    HTTP STATUS CODES — WHICH TO USE WHERE
================================================================

    200 OK           → GET success / PUT success
    201 Created      → POST success (something was created)
    204 No Content   → DELETE success (nothing to return)
    400 Bad Request  → validation failed (@Valid)
    404 Not Found    → ID does not exist in DB


================================================================
    THE 3 LEVELS — WHICH TO USE WHEN
================================================================

    LEVEL 1 — BEGINNER (tutorials, learning):
        @GetMapping, return User directly, orElse(null)

    LEVEL 2 — INTERMEDIATE (real projects):
        @GetMapping, return ResponseEntity<User>
        proper 404 with ResponseEntity.notFound().build()

    LEVEL 3 — PROFESSIONAL (production APIs):
        ResponseEntity + proper status codes
        @Valid for input validation
        @PatchMapping for partial updates
        existsById() before deleting


================================================================
    KEY RULE TO REMEMBER
================================================================

    @GetMapping              = shortcut for @RequestMapping(method = GET)
    @PostMapping             = shortcut for @RequestMapping(method = POST)
    @PutMapping              = shortcut for @RequestMapping(method = PUT)
    @PatchMapping            = shortcut for @RequestMapping(method = PATCH)
    @DeleteMapping           = shortcut for @RequestMapping(method = DELETE)

    All shortcuts introduced in Spring 4.3 — both work exactly the same.
    Shortcuts are cleaner and shorter — always prefer them over @RequestMapping.

    PUT vs PATCH:
    PUT    → send all fields   → replaces entire object
    PATCH  → send some fields  → updates only what you send

    return null          → basic, no proper HTTP status
    ResponseEntity       → professional, controls exact HTTP status code

